04201nam a22006495i 9781503633094DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20222022cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021055751  a97815036330947 a10.1515/97815036330942doi  a(DE-B1597)641543  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aPN49b.S5545 2022 4aPN49b.S5545 2022 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a823.009/353223/eng/202203161 aSimpson, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEngaging Violence :bCivility and the Reach of Literature /cDavid Simpson. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultural Memory in the Present00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Civility and Literature and Their Discontents -- t2. Civil Beginnings -- t3. Philosophy Polite and Politic: Shaftesbury’s “Inmate Controller” -- t4. The Displacement of Civility: Violence in a Widening World -- t5. Civility after 1989: Romancing Small Groups -- t6. The Reach of Literature -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRecent thinking has resuscitated civility as an important paradigm for engaging with a violence that must be deemed endemic to our lives. But, while it is widely acknowledged that civility works against violence, and that literature generates or accompanies civility and engenders tolerance, civility has also been understood as violence in disguise, and literature, which has only rarely sought to claim the power of violence, has often been accused of inciting it. This book sets out to describe the ways in which these words—violence, literature and civility—and the concepts they evoke are mutually entangled, and the uses to which these entanglements have been put. Simpson's argument follows a broadly historical trajectory through the long modern period from the Renaissance to the present, drawing on the work of historians, political scientists, literary scholars and philosophers. The result is a distinctly new argument about the complex and often mystified entanglements between literature, civility and violence in the anglophone Atlantic sphere. What now are our expectations of civility and literature, separately and together? How do these long-familiar but residually imprecise concepts stand up to the demands of the modern world? Simpson's argument is that, despite and perhaps because of their imperfect conceptualization, both persist as important protocols for the critique of violence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCourtesy in literature. 0aLiterature and morals. 0aLiterature and society. 0aViolence in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aLiterature.  aaesthetics.  acivil society.  acivility.  aliterary theory.  apedagogy.  asubalternity.  aviolence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363309440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503633094423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503633094/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles